    "summary": "The Anschluss (German for annexation or connection) was the incorporation of Austria into [[event:2653|Nazi Germany]] on March 12–13, 1938. German troops crossed the Austrian border on March 12 after Austrian Chancellor Kurt Schuschnigg, under intense pressure from Hitler, resigned and was replaced by the pro-Nazi Arthur Seyss-Inquart, who invited German forces in. Hitler entered Vienna on March 14 to mass crowds, and Austria was officially incorporated into the German Reich on March 13.\n\nThe union of Germany and Austria had long been desired by pan-German nationalists and had been explicitly prohibited by the [[event:2644|Treaty of Versailles]] and the Treaty of Saint-Germain. Hitler's success in achieving it without military resistance or serious international protest demonstrated the weakness of the collective security system. Britain and France issued diplomatic protests but took no action. Mussolini, who had previously opposed German expansion into Austria as threatening Italian interests in the Tyrol, now acquiesced as part of his growing alignment with Germany.\n\nAustria's 6.5 million population substantially increased Germany's human and economic resources. Austrian Jews — approximately 200,000 people — were immediately subjected to brutal persecution that exceeded even what German Jews had experienced since 1933, with mass arrests, forced emigration, and public humiliation. The speed and severity of anti-Jewish measures in Vienna provided a preview of the violence that would eventually become the [[event:2660|Holocaust]].",
